If you're just getting started with Rust, one of the first things you'll try is reading input from the user. Simple enough, right?But then... Rust makes you , pass it by mutable reference, and . Why all the steps? Why can’t we just write let age:  and call it a day?By the end, you’ll have a solid grasp of how to , , and  user input in Rust.use std::io;

fn main() {
    println!("Enter a number:");

    let mut input = String::new();
    io::stdin().read_line(&mut input).expect("Failed to read line");

    // Trim whitespace and parse the string to an i32
    let number: i32 = input.trim().parse().expect("Please type a number!");

    println!("You entered: {}", number);
}

 reads user input into a . removes spaces and the newline character () from the input. converts the string to an integer. handles errors if the input isn't a valid number.


  ❗ If the input is invalid:
If the user types something like  instead of a number,  will fail, and  will show an error message.


  🔍 Now, let's break down the line of code after the first print statement
let mut input = String::new();

✅ let
This is Rust's variable declaration keyword—it means "create a new variable." If you come from the JavaScript land, this must be familiar!🔄 mut
This means the variable is , or . By default, Rust variables are  (), so you need mut when you want to modify the variable later—like filling it with user input.📦 input
This is the . You can name it anything, but input is a descriptive name in this context. 🧵 String::new()
This creates a . is scalable (growable) type in Rust. is an  that returns a new, empty .In other words, we are creating an empty container ready to be filled eventually. Now this piece of code stumped me!io::stdin().read_line(&mut input).expect("Failed to read line");

let mut input = String::new();only creates an empty string. It's like saying Hey computer, get me a blank notepad (a mutable string) that I can write in later.But at this point, the notepad is still —there’s  yet.


  💬 So how do we get user input?
That’s what this part does:io::stdin()
    .read_line(&mut input)
    .expect("Failed to read line");

Let's break this down. Shall we?: Accesses the  (your keyboard): Reads a line of text from the user and puts 
it into the  string just like  in C.: If something goes wrong, expect an error and deliberately crash the program. To summarize it, The first  the storage and the second  it with user input.Try to read input. If it fails, don't continue—just stop and show this message.


  🔍 Why not just accept a number directly?
Because when you type into a terminal or command line, you’re —even if it looks like a number.For example: when you type , the program receives as . So what you typed is , not a number. Even  is a string until you *(or parse) it.


  🧠 Why doesn’t Rust just handle that automatically?
Because Rust is . It won’t assume what you meant—it makes you say it explicitly.The terminal only gives you .You must convert  manually.Rust does this on purpose for clarity, safety, and control.
